"""
mkt-context | Numbers 3 | The Levitical census and firstborn substitution
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-numbers-3-3.py

Numbers 3 (51 verses) establishes the Levites as the corporate substitute for all
firstborn Israelites — the mechanism by which YHWH's Passover claim on the firstborn
is institutionally satisfied. Key historical/archaeological context:

1. ANE firstborn dedication: Many ANE cultures dedicated firstborn to their deity
   (Phoenicia/Carthage offered child sacrifice; Israel replaces this with redemption
   and Levitical substitution).
2. Concentric camp theology: Tabernacle center → Moses/Aaron east; Kohath south,
   Gershon west, Merari north → twelve tribes in four compass groups. This architecture
   mirrors ANE sacred-space cosmology with the holy radiating outward.
3. The Kohathites carry the most dangerous items (ark, lampstand, altars). The
   holiness-as-fire theology: approach correctly = life; wrongly = death (Num 4:15).
4. The 22,000 / 22,273 arithmetic forces an acknowledgment of the substitution
   system's limits: 273 surplus firstborn require monetary redemption at 5 shekels
   each — the same five-shekel rate Jesus' parents paid at his temple presentation
   (Luke 2:22-24; fulfilling Exod 13:2, 13; Num 3:47-48).
5. The netunim vocabulary (v.9: 'wholly given') anticipates the post-exilic Nethinim
   (temple servants, Ezra 2:43; 8:20) — an institutional memory of Levitical gifting.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent


def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}


def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")


def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


NUMBERS = {
    "3": {
        "1": "<p>The phrase <em>these are the descendants of Aaron and Moses</em> (תּוֹלְדֹת אַהֲרֹן וּמֹשֶׁה) uses the toledot formula that structures Genesis (Gen 2:4; 5:1; etc.). In Genesis, each toledot introduces a new generation and a new narrative. Here the formula introduces not a new genealogy but an account of Aaron's priestly line — implying that the priestly system is itself a new creation narrative centered on the mountain of God.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Aaron's four sons in birth order: Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, Ithamar. Nadab and Abihu are listed first because they are the eldest, even though they die before the main narrative of Numbers begins. Ancient priestly genealogies regularly preserved the names of those who died without successors as a form of honorable memorial — their names are not erased despite their failure.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The sons are described as <em>anointed priests who were ordained</em> (מְשִׁיחֵי כֵהֻנָּה אֲשֶׁר-מִלֵּא יָדָם). <em>Milleˀ yadam</em> (filled their hands) is the technical idiom for priestly ordination — the priest's hands are filled with the portion of the sacrifice that belongs to him. The anointing with oil and the filling of the hand are the two ritual acts that make a priest a priest.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Nadab and Abihu died before the LORD when they offered <em>eish zarah</em> (אֵשׁ זָרָה, unauthorized fire) in the wilderness of Sinai. The parenthetical <em>they had no sons</em> explains why the priestly succession passed to Eleazar and Ithamar without contest. In ANE priestly systems, priestly office was hereditary — a son who died without sons created an inheritance crisis. The Torah resolves it with the surviving brothers.</p>",
        "5": "<p>YHWH's speech to Moses initiating the Levitical institution. The command structure throughout Numbers 3 is consistent: YHWH commands → Moses executes. The Levitical system is a divine appointment, not a human organizational decision. The distinction matters: Aaron and his sons did not recruit the Levites; YHWH assigned them.</p>",
        "6": "<p><em>Haqˀrev ˀet-maṭṭeh Levi</em> (הַקְרֵב אֶת-מַטֵּה לֵוִי, bring forward the tribe of Levi) — the root <em>qarav</em> (to draw near, present) is the same root as <em>qorban</em> (sacrifice/offering). The Levites are presented to Aaron as an act of sacred drawing-near — their presentation has the quality of an offering. They are brought near to serve the one who offers.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The Levites' duties include serving Aaron and the whole congregation <em>lifney ˀohel moˁed</em> (before the tent of meeting). The tent of meeting is the spatial center of Israel's life; everything significant in Numbers happens 'before the tent.' Serving before the tent is serving at the intersection of the divine and the human — the place where YHWH meets Israel.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The Levites are responsible for <em>kol kˀley ˀohel moˁed</em> (all the furnishings of the tent of meeting). The word <em>kˀley</em> (vessels/instruments/furnishings) covers everything from the great bronze altar to the smallest hook. Caring for the instruments of worship is itself a sacred act — the maintenance of the apparatus of encounter between Israel and YHWH.</p>",
        "9": "<p><em>Netunin netunin hemah li</em> (נְתֻנִים נְתֻנִים הֵמָּה לִי) — 'they are wholly given to him from among the Israelites.' The doubled participial form (netunin netunin) emphasizes total givenness — not partly assigned but entirely. This vocabulary of <em>natan</em> (to give) gives rise to the post-exilic <em>Nethinim</em> (נְתִינִים, Ezra 2:43; 8:20) — the temple servants below the Levites. The institutional memory of Levitical 'given-ness' persists through the return from exile.</p>",
        "10": "<p><em>Hazzer hamˀera zohar yummat</em> (הַזָּר הַקָּרֵב יוּמָת, the unauthorized person who comes near shall be put to death). This is the enforcement clause for the Levitical buffer system: the Levites mediate between Israel and the tabernacle; any non-Levite who bypasses this mediation and approaches holy space dies. The theological claim: unrestricted access to divine holiness is lethal. The Levitical guard exists to preserve life, not to restrict worship.</p>",
        "11": "<p>A new divine speech introducing the firstborn-substitution theology. The speech breaks the pattern of clan-by-clan assignment to state the foundational principle: why Levites? What makes this tribe suitable for this role? The answer is not inherent Levitical superiority but historical divine claim on the firstborn.</p>",
        "12": "<p><em>ˀani laqaḥti ˀet-haLˀviyim... taḥat kol-bˀkhor</em> — I have taken the Levites in place of every firstborn (בְּכוֹר, bekhor). <em>Taḥat</em> (under, in place of) is the substitution preposition used in Genesis 22:13 (the ram in place of Isaac) and throughout the sacrificial system. The Levites are the corporate substitute — each Levite stands in place of one Israelite firstborn. The substitution theology of the OT operates at individual level (ram for Isaac) and corporate level (Levites for firstborn Israel).</p>",
        "13": "<p><em>Ki li kol-bˀkhor</em> (כִּי לִי כָּל-בְּכוֹר, for every firstborn is mine). The foundational claim established at the Passover (Ex 13:2): YHWH killed the Egyptian firstborn; therefore all Israelite firstborn belong to him by right of redemption. The Levites do not own their service role; they were taken to fill a slot already consecrated. They are substitutes occupying the space that belongs to another.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The command is given in the wilderness of Sinai (<em>midbar Sinai</em>) — the same setting as all the legal material of Leviticus and the early chapters of Numbers. Sinai is the location of covenant-law-giving; the Levitical census is one more element of the covenant order established from the mountain.</p>",
        "15": "<p><em>Mibben ḥodesh wamaˁlah</em> (מִבֶּן-חֹדֶשׁ וָמַעְלָה, from a month old and upward). The military census counted from 20 years old (Num 1:3); the Levitical census counts from one month old — including infants who could not yet serve. The difference reflects the nature of the dedication: Levites are priestly people from birth, not warriors called up at military age. The one-month threshold may reflect the ancient practice of not registering infants until they had survived the most vulnerable period.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Moses counted them at the LORD's command (<em>ˁal-pi YHWH</em>, literally 'at the mouth of YHWH'). The census data is not Moses' administration alone; it is divine dictation. The precision of the numbers — exact to the unit — reflects the care of a divine ledger, not a rough administrative head-count.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The three sons of Levi: Gershon, Kohath, and Merari. These names appear already in Gen 46:11 and Ex 6:16. The three-clan structure of the Levites is as foundational as the twelve-tribe structure of Israel — it divides the priestly service into three functional groups that will be assigned to different aspects of the tabernacle's care and different positions in the camp.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Gershon's two sub-clans: Libni and Shimei. <em>Gershon</em> may derive from <em>gerush</em> (expulsion/sojourn) — the name of the one who lives as a stranger. The Gershonites are the westernmost Levites, camping behind the tabernacle. Their name and position (at the back, in the direction of the wilderness sunset) may carry a theological resonance of the sojourning life.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Kohath's four sub-clans: Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel. The Kohathites are the most distinguished Levitical clan: Moses and Aaron are Amramites (Amram son of Kohath, Ex 6:18,20). The Kohathite position (south side, closest to the most holy objects) reflects their genealogical proximity to the priestly line.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Merari's two sub-clans: Mahli and Mushi. <em>Merari</em> may derive from <em>marar</em> (bitter). The Merarites camped on the north side and carried the structural components of the tabernacle — the frames, bars, and pillars that constitute the building itself. The heaviest, most structural work was theirs.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The Gershonite clans are listed: Libnites (from Libni) and Shimeites (from Shimei). The clan structure creates an intermediate organizational tier between the three Levitical lines and the individual household. In ANE military and administrative contexts, this three-level hierarchy (tribe → clan → household) was standard governance structure — Israel's organization mirrors the administrative conventions of its ancient context.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Gershon total: 7,500 males from a month old and upward. The count includes infants, meaning the 7,500 represents the full demographic base of the clan, not just the able-bodied adults. The total Levite count will be 22,000 — Gershon contributes roughly a third of the Levitical workforce.</p>",
        "23": "<p>Gershonite position: west side (<em>yarekah hayam</em>, the sea side — literally toward the Mediterranean, i.e., the west). The four compass points around the tabernacle are assigned: east (Moses/Aaron), south (Kohath), west (Gershon), north (Merari). The cardinal directions reflect the ANE cosmological understanding of sacred space radiating outward from a divine center.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The Gershonite clan head: Eliasaph son of Lael. The Levitical clan leaders are named but are not the high priest — they are middle management in the sacred service hierarchy. The name Eliasaph (אֶלְיָסָף, 'God has added/gathered') suggests the theology of divine increase embedded in personal names throughout the tribal period.</p>",
        "25": "<p>Gershonite responsibility: the tabernacle itself (<em>hamishkan</em>), the tent and its covering (<em>weˀohalo umikˀsehu</em>), and the screen at the entrance (<em>umaseḵ petaḥ ˀohel moˁed</em>). They maintained the outer fabric of the sacred space — the curtains and coverings that defined the boundary between the sacred and the common. The fabric guardians preserve the distinction that the purity laws enforce.</p>",
        "26": "<p>The Gershonites also maintained the courtyard hangings, the gate screen, and all the ropes. The rope-and-peg system held the entire tabernacle structure together; without it, the sacred enclosure collapsed. The care of the seemingly mundane (ropes and pegs) is itself a sacred task — the integrity of the worship space depends on the faithfulness of those maintaining its most prosaic components.</p>",
        "27": "<p>Kohath's four sub-clans: Amramites, Izharites, Hebronites, Uzzielites. The Amramites include the family of Moses and Aaron (Ex 6:18-20). The Kohathite position (south) places them between Moses/Aaron (east) and the Merarites (north), creating an arc of Levitical protection around the tabernacle's southern exposure.</p>",
        "28": "<p>Kohath total: 8,600 — the largest of the three Levitical groups, responsible for <em>shomˀrey mishˀmeret haqqodesh</em> (the keepers of the sanctuary charge). The title 'keepers of the sanctuary charge' is the highest of the three Levitical functions — carrying the most holy objects gives the Kohathites a role analogous to the tabernacle's inner guard. The largest clan is assigned the highest-risk responsibility.</p>",
        "29": "<p>Kohathite position: south side (<em>yerekh hadarom</em>). In ANE sacred architecture, the south was often associated with royal presence and judgment. The Kohathites — the royal (Moses) and priestly (Aaron) clan — occupy the south. Their position both reflects and reinforces their function as the most intimately connected group to the divine presence at the center.</p>",
        "30": "<p>Kohathite clan head: Elizaphan son of Uzziel. Elizaphan (אֶלִיצָפָן, 'my God has protected') comes from the youngest sub-clan of Kohath. The leadership of the Kohathite group by an Uzzielite rather than an Amramite (Moses/Aaron's sub-clan) reflects the principle that priestly families do not automatically hold non-priestly Levitical leadership — the two roles are distinct.</p>",
        "31": "<p>Kohathite responsibility: the ark (<em>haˀaron</em>), the table (<em>hashulḥan</em>), the lampstand (<em>hamˀnorah</em>), the altars (<em>hamilmizbeḥot</em>), the sanctuary vessels (<em>kˀley haqqodesh</em>), the curtain (<em>masoḵ</em>), and all their service. These are the furnishings of the holy of holies and the holy place — the objects of direct divine encounter. The ark especially: the place where YHWH met Moses and where atonement was made. Carrying the ark was the most dangerous assignment in the service system.</p>",
        "32": "<p>Eleazar son of Aaron as chief over the Levitical leaders — specifically over those who keep the sanctuary charge. The high priestly family (Aaron's sons) supervises the Levitical service hierarchy. Eleazar's supervisory role foreshadows his prominence after Aaron's death (Num 20:28) and his co-leadership with Joshua in the land distribution (Num 34:17). The priestly line exercises authority over the Levitical line at every level.</p>",
        "33": "<p>Merari's two sub-clans: Mahlites and Mushites. <em>Mahli</em> may relate to <em>ḥoli</em> (illness) — a name that reflects the honest naming of difficult circumstances, common in the OT. The Merarites' assignment to the structural components (frames, bars, pillars) reflects a theology of service: the least glamorous work — maintaining the building's bones — is also sacred service.</p>",
        "34": "<p>Merari total: 6,200 — the smallest of the three groups, assigned the heaviest physical work (the structural components were the most massive items in the tabernacle). The mathematical irony: the fewest workers carried the most weight. The sacred service economy does not distribute labor proportionally to capacity.</p>",
        "35": "<p>Merari clan head: Zuriel son of Abihail. They camp on the north side (<em>yerekh tsapon</em>). In ANE cosmology, the north was often associated with the divine throne (cf. Isa 14:13; Ps 48:2). The Merarites — carriers of the structural skeleton of the tabernacle — occupy the north, the direction associated with divine sovereignty.</p>",
        "36": "<p>Merarite responsibility: the frames (<em>qˀreshey hamishkan</em>), bars (<em>ubˀriḥav</em>), pillars (<em>weˁammudav</em>), and sockets (<em>waˀadanav</em>). The structural components of the tabernacle were made of acacia wood overlaid with gold or bronze — heavy, dense, and numerous. The frames alone (48 boards, each approximately 4.5 meters tall) required significant personnel to carry. The Merarites' 6,200 men transported the equivalent of a large building's load-bearing elements.</p>",
        "37": "<p>Merarites also maintained the pillars, sockets, pegs, and ropes of the surrounding courtyard. The courtyard — the outer boundary of sacred space — required its own structural maintenance. From the innermost holy objects (Kohath) to the outermost structural pegs (Merari), the entire tabernacle complex was under continuous Levitical care.</p>",
        "38": "<p>Moses, Aaron, and Aaron's sons camp on the east side, before the tabernacle toward the sunrise (<em>qˀdemah mizraḥah</em>). East = sunrise = the direction of light and life in ANE symbolism. The priestly family guards the gate of the tabernacle, the entrance from the east — the direction from which God's presence comes (cf. Ezek 43:2, the divine glory entering the temple from the east). Any unauthorized person approaching from any direction encounters a Levitical guard first.</p>",
        "39": "<p>Total Levites: 22,000. The aggregate of all three groups counted from one month old. The total is suspiciously round — the separate clan totals (7,500 + 8,600 + 6,200 = 22,300) don't add up to 22,000 exactly; the discrepancy of 300 has generated extensive discussion. Some manuscripts and the Samaritan Pentateuch adjust the numbers. The 22,000 figure may be an administrative total that excludes certain categories counted differently.</p>",
        "40": "<p>YHWH commands a parallel census of firstborn Israelite males from one month old — the same age threshold as the Levites. The parallelism is deliberate: both censuses use the same unit (one month and upward) to create a directly comparable population for the substitution transaction. The divine arithmetic is careful before the exchange is made.</p>",
        "41": "<p><em>Laqaḥta ˀet-haLˀviyim li... taḥat kol-bˀkhor</em> — take the Levites for me in place of all the firstborn. The substitution formula is repeated from v.12. The redundancy is legal: in ancient legal contexts, important clauses were restated to ensure that both parties (God and Israel) understood the terms of the transaction. The Levitical substitution is a bilateral covenant provision.</p>",
        "42": "<p>Moses counted all the firstborn as the LORD commanded. The count is a census of those who belong to God — the firstborn who survived when YHWH passed through Egypt. Each firstborn male represents a life that death passed over; now the census registers them for exchange with the Levites who will serve in their place.</p>",
        "43": "<p>Firstborn total: 22,273. The precision of the number is striking — not a round figure but an exact count. The 273-person surplus over the 22,000 Levites creates the arithmetic problem that vv.46-50 resolve. The exactness of the census reflects the theological claim: every firstborn life that was spared at Passover is personally known to YHWH and is individually registered.</p>",
        "44": "<p>Another divine speech inaugurating the specific instructions for the surplus. The institutional mechanics are given sequentially: first the principle (v.12-13), then the census (v.14-43), then the transaction details (v.44-51). The step-by-step structure ensures the logic is transparent before the exchange is executed.</p>",
        "45": "<p>The substitution formula: Levites in place of (taḥat) all the firstborn Israelites; Levitical livestock in place of Israelite livestock. The substitution extends to the animals — the firstborn of livestock were also consecrated to YHWH (Ex 13:12-15). The Levites and their herds comprehensively replace Israel's firstborn and their herds.</p>",
        "46": "<p>For the 273 firstborn who exceed the number of Levites, a monetary redemption is required. The system acknowledges its own insufficiency: 22,000 Levites cannot individually substitute for 22,273 firstborn. The 273 'unexchanged' firstborn require a different mechanism — money. The transition from personal substitution to monetary redemption prefigures a longer theological trajectory: the move from animal sacrifice to the once-for-all redemption that money itself cannot buy (1 Pet 1:18-19).</p>",
        "47": "<p>Five shekels per person, reckoned in the sanctuary shekel (twenty gerahs to the shekel). The five-shekel rate for firstborn redemption is the same rate Jesus' parents paid at his presentation in the temple (Luke 2:22-24). The Mosaic law required the redemption of firstborn sons (Ex 13:13; Num 18:15-16). Jesus — the firstborn son of Mary — was redeemed at the temple according to this exact provision. The one who would ultimately redeem humanity entered the temple as the one who first needed to be redeemed under the law he came to fulfill.</p>",
        "48": "<p>The redemption money goes to Aaron and his sons. The priestly household receives the monetary compensation for the 273 unsubstituted firstborn. The Aaronide priesthood is economically supported by the surplus of the substitution system — the gap between what the Levites could cover and what the firstborn census required becomes the economic provision for the priests.</p>",
        "49": "<p>Moses collected the redemption money from those who exceeded the number redeemed by the Levites. The transaction is complete: 22,000 Levites substituted person-for-person, 273 additional firstborn redeemed with five shekels each. The system's precision — counting to the unit, redeeming by the unit — reflects the conviction that every life claimed at Passover is individually significant.</p>",
        "50": "<p>The total redemption money: 1,365 shekels in sanctuary weight. The arithmetic is exact: 273 × 5 = 1,365. The sanctuary shekel at 20 gerahs was the highest-value standard measure; the redemption price is calculated in the most precise and honored unit of measure. The firstborn are worth the best standard of accounting.</p>",
        "51": "<p>Moses gave the redemption money to Aaron and his sons at the LORD's command. The chapter ends as it began — with the Aaronide priesthood at the center and Moses as the executor of divine instruction. The entire elaborate institution of the Levitical census, the firstborn census, and the substitution transaction was designed to support this single outcome: a functioning priestly system with a Levitical workforce to maintain it and a firstborn theology to justify it.</p>",
    },
}


def main():
    data = load_comm("mkt-context", "numbers")
    merge_comm(data, NUMBERS)
    save_comm("mkt-context", "numbers", data)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
